I now have all the information needed. Let me compile a complete, working example.

---

## Premiere Pro UXP Plugin - Complete Working Example

### Requirements
- **Premiere Pro v25.6 or later** (UXP support is now in the release version as of December 2025)
- **UXP Developer Tool v2.2 or later** (install via Creative Cloud Desktop)

---

### 1. Working manifest.json

```json
{
  "id": "com.example.myplugin",
  "name": "My UXP Plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.html",
  "host": {
    "app": "premierepro",
    "minVersion": "25.1.0"
  },
  "manifestVersion": 5,
  "entrypoints": [
    {
      "id": "mainpanel",
      "type": "panel",
      "label": {
        "default": "My UXP Plugin"
      },
      "minimumSize": {
        "width": 230,
        "height": 200
      },
      "maximumSize": {
        "width": 2000,
        "height": 2000
      },
      "preferredDockedSize": {
        "width": 230,
        "height": 300
      },
      "preferredFloatingSize": {
        "width": 400,
        "height": 300
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**CRITICAL**: The host app must be `"premierepro"` (all lowercase). Using `"PremierePro"` (with capitals) will cause the "Host Application specified is not available" error.

---

### 2. Minimal index.html

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>My UXP Plugin</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Adobe Clean, sans-serif;
      padding: 16px;
      background: #323232;
      color: #e1e1e1;
    }
    button {
      padding: 8px 16px;
      margin: 4px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h2>Hello Premiere Pro</h2>
  <p id="status">Ready</p>
  <button id="testBtn">Test API</button>

  <script>
    const ppro = require("premierepro");

    document.getElementById("testBtn").addEventListener("click", async () => {
      try {
        const app = await ppro.app;
        const project = await app.getActiveProject();
        const projectName = project ? await project.getName() : "No project open";
        document.getElementById("status").textContent = "Project: " + projectName;
      } catch (err) {
        document.getElementById("status").textContent = "Error: " + err.message;
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

### 3. File Structure

```
my-uxp-plugin/
  manifest.json
  index.html
```

That is all you need for a minimal plugin.

---

### 4. Step-by-Step Loading Instructions

**Step 1: Enable Developer Mode in Premiere Pro**
1. Open Premiere Pro (v25.6+)
2. Go to **Edit > Preferences > Plugins** (Windows) or **Premiere Pro > Settings > Plugins** (Mac)
3. Check **Enable developer mode**
4. Restart Premiere Pro

**Step 2: Load Plugin via UXP Developer Tool**
1. Open **UXP Developer Tool** (UDT v2.2+)
2. Click **Add Plugin**
3. Navigate to your plugin folder and select `manifest.json`
4. Click **Load** (or **Load & Watch** for live reload during development)
5. In Premiere Pro, go to **Window > UXP Plugins > My UXP Plugin**

**Alternative: Manual Installation (without UDT)**
Place your plugin folder at:
- **macOS**: `~/Library/Application Support/Adobe/UXP/Plugins/External/com.example.myplugin_1.0.0/`
- **Windows**: `%APPDATA%\Adobe\UXP\Plugins\External\com.example.myplugin_1.0.0\`

The folder name must follow the format: `{plugin-id}_{version-number}`

---

### Common Issues and Fixes

| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| "Host Application specified is not available" | Use `"premierepro"` (lowercase), not `"PremierePro"` |
| Plugin loads in UDT but not in Premiere | Enable developer mode in Premiere Pro Settings > Plugins |
| Plugin doesn't appear after loading | Check Window > UXP Plugins menu |
| Changes to manifest.json not reflected | Must unload and reload plugin manually |

---

